Introdution¶

Businesses in the hospitality industry, such as hotels, rely heavily on customer feedback and popularity to attract and retain customers. However, even popular hotels may have flaws that can negatively impact their reputation and revenue. Reviews provide valuable insights for both businesses and potential customers, as they help to minimize risk by providing information about the pros and cons of a particular hotel.

This project conducts exploratory data analysis (EDA) on a dataset of customer reviews for a well-known hotel in Singapore. The EDA process begins by cleaning and preprocessing the data, including handling missing values, converting data types, and extracting relevant information from the review text. Visualization techniques, such as bar plots, histograms, and word clouds, are used to understand the distribution of ratings and identify common words used in the reviews. To further analyze the data, natural language processing (NLP) techniques are applied to study the sentiments of the reviews. Additionally, machine learning techniques are employed to build predictive models that classify reviews into positive and negative categories based on their ratings. Through these techniques, the project aims to uncover patterns and insights about the hotel and draw conclusions based on the findings.

Aims and Objectives¶

The aim of this project is to provide a comprehensive analysis of the hotel reviews data and gain insights that can be used by the hotel management to improve their customer satisfaction and also help the user see the things that they should consider before visiting the hotel. The objectives of the project are to clean and preprocess thedata, visualize the data to uncover patterns, and use machine learning techniques to build predictive models that can classify the reviews. By achieving these objectives, we hope to contribute to the hotel management's efforts to improve the quality of their services and customer experience. In Conclusion the project targets- To perform EDA on the hotel reviews dataset to understand the distribution of ratings and identify common words used in the reviews.

  • To use NLP techniques to analyze the sentiment of the reviews and see how it varies over the years.
  • To find the features that are popular about the hotel using reviews.
  • To build predictive models using machine learning techniques that can classify the reviews into positive and negative categories based on the ratings.
  • To present our findings and conclusions, along with recommendations for future improvements, to the hotel management.

Data¶

Credibility¶

The data pertains to the renowned Marina Bay Sands hotel. The data was sourced from Tripadvisor.com and covers the time period from January 2015 to October 2022, based on the dates of stay reported by visitors. A total of 10,232 records were collected through the use of Python web scraping, utilizing the Beautifulsoup4 library for parsing and regular expressions for extraction.

About the data¶

The data overall brings alot of information that can be used to explore interesting facts and performancees of the hotel.vThe positive aspect of the dataset is its extensive coverage of a period of more than 5 years, including a large number of ratings. This level of detail enhances the credibility of our conclusions and allows for the application of natural language processing (NLP) algorithms and sentiment analysis. Additionally, the data includes sufficient information for statistical analysis. However, some of the columns may not be relevant for our purposes and the volume of reviews may pose a challenge for sentiment analysis.

Clean / Preprocess Data¶

As the column we are going to use for the processing is the content column. This column holds all the user feedback. This data needs some cleaning and processing as the data would have unneccesary information and characters that wont be usefull for us. The cleaning involves removig null values, but the preprocessing part involves:

  • Remove Stop Words
  • Remove non-alphabetic characters
  • Make all letters Lowercase
Remove Null Values¶

To start , Lets clean rows that have any null values. This will help us to avoid any program errors and will increase credibility of results.

Preprocess Reviews¶

Remove Punctuation Marks¶

It might be beneficial to remove punctuation marks from the review text as they may potentially impact the operation of certain sentiment analysis algorithms.

In [ ]:
def remove_punct(revText):
    #creats a translator table 
    translator = str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation)
    cleanText = revText.translate(translator)
    return cleanText
In [ ]:
#creates a df cleanReviews that is the processed column
df['cleanReviews'] = df['content'].apply(remove_punct)

Remove Stop Words¶

Stopwords, which are words that do not significantly contribute to the meaning of a sentence (e.g. "a," "an," and "the"), may be removed from the review text to potentially enhance the accuracy of the sentiment analysis model.

In [ ]:
#To remove stopwords from df, we use the apply() method and a lambda function that filters out stopwords.
stopWords = set(stopwords.words('english'))
df['cleanReviews'] = df['cleanReviews'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join([word for word in x.split() if word not in stopWords]))

NLP¶

Natural Language Processing (NLP) focuses on making it possible for computers to read, understand, and generate human language. It is important because it enables computers to process and analyze large amounts of natural language data, which is critical for tasks such as automatic translation, sentiment analysis, and topic modeling.
In this study, we will be using NLP techniques to process and analyze a dataset of reviews in order to explore various aspects of the text. By applying NLP techniques such as text preprocessing, feature extraction, and machine learning algorithms, we will be able to gain insights and draw conclusions from the review data. Our goal is to see if we are able to list some popular features and things about the hotel that people mentioned in the comments.
In the folllowing part we start by taking the pre processed reviews and explore them to find something interesting from the reviews. To start, lets join all the reviews and tokenize all the words to search and process.

Sentiment Analysis¶

Sentiment analysis is a natural language processing technique that aims to determine the sentiment or emotion behind a piece of text. It is commonly used to analyze customer reviews, social media posts, and other forms of online feedback to understand how people feel about a product, service, or brand.

By analyzing the sentiment of user reviews, you can gain valuable insights into the thoughts and feelings of your customers. This can help you identify trends and patterns in the reviews, and understand what your customers like and dislike about your product or service. It can also help you identify any negative sentiment that may be impacting your brand reputation, and take steps to address any issues that may arise.

There are several different approaches to performing sentiment analysis, including machine learning algorithms, rule-based systems, and lexicon-based methods. Regardless of the approach used, the goal is to classify text as positive, negative, or neutral, and often to quantify the degree of positivity or negativity. As we can see we have a large data, it will be more credible to use last three years data. This will increase the credibility and will give us results that will be helpful for the hotel.

For our sentiment Analysis , we used two models

Vader¶

VADER(Valence Aware Dictionary and Sentiment Reasoner) is a tool for analyzing the sentiment of social media text. It uses a set of rules and a pre-defined list of words to identify the sentiment of a text.

Roberta¶

RoBERTa(Robustly Optimized BERT Approach) is a language model created by Facebook that can be customized for specific tasks. It is based on transformers and uses a pre-trained model that can be modified with task-specific layers.

Lemmatize Words¶

Lemmatization is a technique that can be used to reduce words to their base form, which is known as a lemma. This technique is often used in natural language processing tasks as a preprocessing step to improve the performance of machine learning models. By reducing inflected forms of a word to a common base form, lemmatization can help the model better understand the context and sentiment of the text. For example, lemmatization would convert the words "running," "ran," and "runs" to the base form "run." This can help the model more accurately analyze the sentiment of a review or other piece of text.

In [ ]:
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

Vader Sentiment Analysis¶

In [ ]:
senti_Analyze = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
#Sample Test
senti_Analyze.polarity_scores('I am so angry i will kill you')
Out[ ]:
{'neg': 0.681, 'neu': 0.319, 'pos': 0.0, 'compound': -0.861}

As seen above the sentence provided has a very negative sentiment, and it contains no positive sentiment. Due to the high negativity of the sentence the compound score is also in negative.

  • The term 'neg' refers to a negative sentiment score that indocates that the model identified a negative emotion or sentiment
  • The term 'neu' refers to a neutral sentiment score that indicates that the model thinks its not not strongly negative or positive
  • The term 'pos' refers to a positive sentiment score that indocates that the model identified a positive emotion or sentiment
  • The compound score combines the positive, negative, and neutral scores into a single score that ranges from -1 to 1. A score of -1 indicates a very negative sentiment, a score of 0 indicates a neutral sentiment, and a score of 1 indicates a very positive sentiment.

We start by creating a function that we can use to find the polarity scores. Then we can iterate through the dataset like we did ealier.

In [ ]:
#function tokenizes and stores the polarity scores in a dictionary 
def roberta_polarityScores(example):
    encoded_text = tokenizer(example, return_tensors = 'pt')
    output = Model2(**encoded_text)
    scores = output[0][0].detach().numpy()
    scores = softmax(scores)
    scores_dict = {
        'roberta_neg' : scores[0],
        'roberta_neu' : scores[1],
        'roberta_pos' : scores[2]   
    }
    #returns polarity scores
    return scores_dict
In [ ]:
#create a dataframe of 1000 rows
rob_df_1000 = df_Sorted.head(1000)
#store the scores
results = {}
for i, r in tqdm(rob_df_1000.iterrows(), total = len(rob_df_1000)):
    try:
        review = r['cleanReviews']
        userId = r['user_id']
        vader_Results = senti_Analyze.polarity_scores(review)
        new_vader_Results = {}
        for key, value in vader_Results.items():
            new_vader_Results[f"vader_{key}"] = value

        roberta_Results = roberta_polarityScores(review)
        new_vader_Results.update(roberta_Results)
        results[userId] = new_vader_Results
    except RuntimeError:
        print(f'error for id{userId}')

Conclusion¶

The main objective of this project was to assess the performance and current situation of the Sand Bay Hotel through the analysis of historical and recent customer feedback. Initially, we examined the variation in user feedback over the years and correlated it with the hotel's performance. Our findings showed that as user feedback increased, the average rating significantly decreased and has not fully recovered to this day. However, the hotel has made efforts to improve its services and is anticipated to receive its best user feedback in the next two years.

In the second part of the project, we analyzed the prominent features of the hotel and discovered that the pool, room, and hotel view were the most frequently mentioned.
Finally, we performed sentiment analysis on the recent years' dataset using two strong models. The results indicated that the hotel reviews had a positive sentiment and, considering the improving average rating, the results were convincing. Upon comparison of the models, we found that the Roberta model provided the most accurate sentiment analysis.

There is potential to further explore the data in several ways. For instance, the ratings can be analyzed to determine the number of 1-star ratings the hotel received in past years. The word exploration could be extended to identify the words most frequently mentioned in past years, such as whether the pool or hotel view was more frequently mentioned in a particular year. Additionally, the comments can be analyzed to determine if they were mentioned in a positive or negative context. Finally, more and stronger sentiment analysis models can be tested to determine the most effective model for processing sentiments. Overall, the results of our analysis showed that the Sand Bay Hotel has received largely positive sentiments in recent years, with the potential for further improvement through the continued analysis of customer feedback and the implementation of effective strategies.
